# The Aiel · the People of the Dragon, who do not touch a sword

The Aiel are the fierce desert people of the Three-fold Land, a harsh waste they have made their home. They are veiled spear-fighters who will not touch a sword, and they live by ji'e'toh, the strict honor-code of obligation and shame that governs every act between them. Theirs is a life shaped by hardship and by a discipline that outsiders rarely understand.

Beneath that warrior fierceness lies a hidden truth. The Aiel are secretly the broken remnant of a once-pacifist people, sworn to serve the Aes Sedai — a history concealed in the glass columns of Rhuidean, where the old blood and the old oath can still be remembered. The refusal to touch a sword is the last trace of what they once were.

They are bound to prophecy as well as to memory. The Aiel are foretold to follow He Who Comes with the Dawn — the Dragon, of the old blood — to their destiny and their near-ruin. To follow him is both their fulfillment and the breaking that prophecy promises.

The Aiel emerge as a natural force in the Pattern: not channeled current, not the Dream or the spirit, but an embodied people of the world, flesh and oath and spear. Their nature is natural because they are one of the worldly powers the Wheel turns through — a living people whose choices, not whose magic, shape the age.
